      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-01-29T05:59:57Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "In this new scheme of engine API, TRIGGERER permission becomes useless w/o READER one. So, we are backtracking on earlier use case of triggering internal jobs from public ones. This is probably fine, but I think we should automatically grant READER to users with TRIGGERER access.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 203,
        "startChar": 2,
        "endLine": 204,
        "endChar": 72
      },
      "revId": "76d40cf364202b36ecd806ec2ca2ea98a1164c51",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "5cd18b4e_b0caf157",
        "filename": "scheduler/appengine/apiservers/scheduler.go",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 204,
      "author": {
        "id": 1002539
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-01-29T06:33:33Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I forgot about this case :( One possible solution in the spirit of this CL is to introduce PEEKER role which is even less powerful than READER. It can only be used to detect absence/presence of jobs. Then TRIGGERERs will automatically be PEEKERS, but not READERS.\n\nGetVisibleJobs and friends will check PEEKER access, and API handlers that return data (job listing etc) will additionally check READER access.\n\nThis sort of makes sense, since for triggering internal jobs from public ones we must disclose the existance of internal jobs anyway (since they are referenced by ID from public jobs). Thus need to allow for public jobs to \"peek\" on internal one.\n\nWdyt?\n\nIn any case, it is for separate CL. For now I\u0027ll make TRIGGERER implying READER.",
      "parentUuid": "5e650391_87941bda",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 203,
        "startChar": 2,
        "endLine": 204,
        "endChar": 72
      },
